content: In conclusion, practical completion is a crucial stage in the construction process, particularly for property developers. It signifies the end of the project and triggers various important events such as the commencement of the defects liability period and insurance coverage. Failing to meet practical completion can have serious consequences, so it is essential for developers to take steps to ensure that this milestone is reached on time. By following the tips outlined in this article and working closely with their contractors and builders, developers can increase the likelihood of achieving practical completion within the agreed timeframe and to the required standard.
